# Frontend Rules

## Components And Hooks

- Prefer small functional components with clear local state.
- Avoid extracting hooks or utility files too early; only extract when logic is reused or meaningfully simplified.
- Keep effect dependencies correct. Do not suppress lint rules unless there is a documented reason.
- Use derived values directly when simple; avoid adding memoization unless it solves a real render or dependency problem.

## Data Fetching And State

- When calling APIs, validate the response shape before trusting nested data.
- Keep async loading and failure states visible in code.
- Do not remove compatibility branches such as AWS vs legacy fallback unless explicitly requested.
- Prefer defensive handling for optional or partial backend data.

## UX Consistency

- Preserve existing route behavior in `training-report-app/src/App.tsx`, especially off-season gating and redirects.
- Maintain established user-facing labels and training concepts such as week, level, movement, and body rotation.
- For forms and tables, favor clarity and operational usefulness over visual novelty.

## Styling

- Reuse existing Tailwind and CSS patterns already present in the codebase.
- Avoid introducing a new component library without being asked.
- Keep layouts responsive and practical on mobile.

## File-Level Awareness

- `training-report-app/src/pages/ProgressOverview.tsx` already contains domain-specific mapping logic between API data and UI display. Be careful when changing week, movement, or level transformations.
- `training-report-app/src/pages/utils/` holds camp schedule and progress mapping utilities. Prefer updating those shared utilities when behavior truly belongs there.
